headline: This $1 Billion Trump Loan For Three Mile Island Lifts S&P 500 Nuclear Giant
summary: Constellation Energy shares angled higher at Wednesday's stock market open after the Department of Energy announced late Tuesday that the S&P 500 nuclear giant's plans to restart a Three Mile Island reactor is now backed by a $1 billion Trump administration loan.  The Department of Energy loan is expected to cover much of the project's estimated $1.6 billion cost with the first advance expected to make its way to Constellation Energy in Q1 2026.  The nuclear giant first announced it will be firing back up Pennsylvania's Three Mile Island Unit 1 in September 2024 as part of a two-decade long contract with Microsoft to provide power for the tech giant's data centers.

headline: Asian shares retreat in cautious trading ahead of Nvidia profit report
summary: Asian shares retreated in cautious trading Wednesday ahead of an earnings report from Nvidia that is seen as a bellwether for the recent craze for artificial intelligence technology.  Hong Kong’s Hang Seng dropped 0.5% to 25,812.54, while the Shanghai Composite slipped just over 1 points to 3,939.29.  Nvidia was due to report its earnings for the last quarter later in the day.

headline: Wall Street holds steadier, for now, ahead of a crucial couple of tests
summary: The U.S. stock market is holding steadier on Wednesday, for now at least, ahead of a couple huge tests for Wall Street.  The S&P 500 rose 0.2% in early trading, coming off a four-day losing streak, its longest in nearly three months.  It’s been shaky recently, not just day to day but also hour to hour, because of worries that stock prices have shot too high and that the Federal Reserve may not deliver as many revitalizing jolts through lower interest rates as expected.
